    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Well-known evergreen coastal tree with a sturdy trunk and shady, rounded crown, growing to at least 10 m. Bark brown, young branches covered in fine hairs. Leaves oval, leathery and arranges spirally around stems, dark shiny-green above and dull below.</p><p>The abundant small, white, bisexual flowers have a strong and unpleasant smell and give rise to small, round, fleshy black berries. Both leaves and fruit release milky latex if damaged.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9807",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Trees can grow to at least 10 m tall, but are often spreading and merge to form tangles clumps. Leaves about 80 mm long.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9808",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Somalia down the east coast of Africa to South Africa, including some Indian Ocean islands.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Melkbosstrand to Mozambique.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9809",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Usually form tangled coastal forests which often have a dense outer canopy of leaves sculpted by the wind and enclosing a dimly lit interior supported by tangles of horizontal branches. Can occur as elegant sturdy trees with rounded crowns. Widespread and common but are protected, meaning they cannot be cut back or felled without permission.</p><p>Popular as an ornamental and shade tree in coastal gardens. Birds, bats and monkeys eat the fruit. The bark and roots are used in traditional medicine to treat broken bones, fevers and dispel bad dreams. The wood is hard and fine grained and has been used for building boats and other structures. The ripe berries are also said to be edible.&nbsp; Trees do not burn easily and can be used as a firebreak.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9810",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9811",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers<strong> </strong>November to April. Most easily propagated by seed sown in Summer, but can also be grown from cutting.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9812",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The only regional member of the genus and unlikely to be confused with other local trees.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9813",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
